# ============================================================================

# Rule 01 - Enterprise Microservice Policy v2

# Part 2 - Communication & Integration

# ============================================================================

# Communication Philosophy

Microservices collaborate.

They never become dependent on each other.

Communication must preserve

* Loose Coupling
* Independent Deployment
* Fault Isolation
* Version Compatibility
* Scalability

Prefer asynchronous communication whenever business requirements allow.

---

# Communication Decision Matrix

Before connecting two services ask

1. Is an immediate response required?

YES

↓

REST

NO

↓

Event

If the interaction changes business state across services

↓

Saga

If only information is required

↓

REST Query

If notification is sufficient

↓

Kafka Event

---

# REST Communication

Use REST only for

* Immediate user responses
* Query current state
* Validation requests
* Synchronous business operations
* Read operations

REST must never become workflow orchestration.

Avoid long chains like

API

↓

Service A

↓

Service B

↓

Service C

↓

Service D

If this pattern appears

Redesign using events.

---

# Event Driven Communication

Business state changes

Must publish events.

Examples

Lead Created

Lead Qualified

Customer Registered

Appointment Booked

Conversation Started

Payment Received

Workflow Completed

Events notify.

Events never request work.

---

# Domain Events

Domain Events

Remain inside the owning bounded context.

Examples

LeadQualified

LeadAssigned

ConversationClosed

CustomerVerified

Never consume another service's internal domain events.

---

# Integration Events

Integration Events

Are public contracts.

Examples

LeadQualifiedIntegrationEvent

CustomerCreatedIntegrationEvent

PaymentCompletedIntegrationEvent

Only Integration Events cross service boundaries.

---

# Event Versioning

Every Integration Event

Must include

eventId

eventType

eventVersion

occurredAt

tenantId

correlationId

aggregateId

payload

Never break existing event consumers.

Create new versions instead.

---

# Event Ownership

Only the owning service publishes its events.

Example

Lead Service

Publishes

LeadCreated

LeadQualified

LeadAssigned

Customer Service

Never publishes

LeadCreated

Ownership is exclusive.

---

# Kafka Policy

Kafka is used for

Cross-service communication

Workflow progression

Notifications

Analytics

Audit

Background processing

AI pipelines

Media processing

Never use Kafka for request/response.

---

# Outbox Pattern

Every service owns

One Outbox table.

Business transaction

↓

Commit

↓

Outbox Record

↓

Kafka Publisher

↓

Event

Never publish Kafka directly inside business transactions.

---

# Saga Pattern

Distributed business transactions

Must use Saga.

Never use

Two Phase Commit

Distributed Database Transactions

XA

Each Saga defines

Forward Action

Compensation Action

Retry Policy

Timeout

Failure Strategy

---

# Compensation

Every distributed workflow

Must define compensation.

Example

Reserve Slot

↓

Create Appointment

↓

Payment Failed

↓

Cancel Appointment

↓

Release Slot

Compensation restores business consistency.

---

# CQRS

Separate

Write Model

Read Model

When

Read complexity grows

Do not introduce CQRS prematurely.

Use it only when it improves scalability or query performance.

---

# Read Models

Read Models

May be built from

Integration Events

Projection Services

Materialized Views

Read Models never become system of record.

---

# API Gateway

All external requests

Pass through

API Gateway.

Gateway responsibilities

Authentication

Tenant Resolution

Rate Limiting

Routing

Correlation Id

Security Headers

Gateway never contains business logic.

---

# SDK Policy

Cross-service capabilities

Must be accessed through SDKs.

Examples

ai-sdk

workflow-sdk

notification-sdk

media-sdk

plugin-sdk

event-sdk

Never reference another service's internal implementation.

---

# Contracts

Shared Contracts

Contain

DTO

Request Models

Response Models

Enums

Error Models

Never share JPA entities across services.

---

# Anti-Corruption Layer

Every external integration

Must use an ACL.

Examples

WhatsApp

Facebook

Google

Payment Gateway

CRM

Maps

External DTOs never enter the domain directly.

Translate them at the boundary.

---

# Idempotency

Public APIs

Webhooks

Event Consumers

Media Uploads

Payment Processing

Must be idempotent.

Duplicate requests

Must not duplicate business state.

---

# Retry Policy

Every remote communication

Defines

Retry Count

Backoff Strategy

Timeout

Circuit Breaker

Failure Handling

Retries must be safe.

---

# Timeouts

Every REST call

Defines timeout.

Every Kafka consumer

Defines processing timeout.

Every workflow step

Defines execution timeout.

Never allow infinite waits.

---

# Failure Isolation

Failure of one service

Must not stop the platform.

Use

Retry

Fallback

Compensation

DLQ

Graceful degradation

---

# Correlation

Every request

Every event

Every workflow

Must propagate

correlationId

traceId

tenantId

requestId

Never lose traceability.

---

# API Versioning

Public APIs

Must support versioning.

Examples

/api/v1/leads

/api/v2/leads

Never introduce breaking API changes without versioning.

---

# Review Checklist

Before approving verify

✓ Correct communication pattern

✓ REST only when synchronous

✓ Events for notifications

✓ Outbox implemented

✓ Saga required?

✓ Compensation defined

✓ SDK used

✓ No entity sharing

✓ Versioning complete

✓ Correlation propagated

---

# Decision Tree

Before generating communication code ask

1. Is synchronous communication required?
2. Would an event reduce coupling?
3. Does this cross bounded contexts?
4. Is an Integration Event required?
5. Is Saga required?
6. Is an SDK available?
7. Is an ACL required?
8. Is idempotency implemented?
9. Is versioning defined?
10. Can this evolve independently?

If any answer is NO

STOP

Redesign communication before implementation.

