# Rule 01 - Enterprise Microservice Policy v2

# Part 4 - Architecture Governance & Repository Intelligence

# ============================================================================

# Architecture Governance

Architecture is a long-term asset.

Every implementation decision must improve

* Maintainability
* Scalability
* Reliability
* Modularity
* Team Productivity

Never sacrifice architecture for short-term speed.

---

# Repository Governance

The repository represents the architecture.

Every new artifact must have

* One owner
* One purpose
* One location

Never create code with ambiguous ownership.

---

# Repository Intelligence

Before generating any artifact perform repository analysis.

Search for

* Existing Service
* Existing Aggregate
* Existing Entity
* Existing Repository
* Existing Event
* Existing API
* Existing DTO
* Existing Mapper
* Existing SDK
* Existing Plugin
* Existing Workflow
* Existing Prompt
* Existing Configuration

Prefer reuse.

Never duplicate.

---

# Duplicate Detection

If similar functionality exists

Evaluate

Reuse

↓

Extension

↓

Composition

↓

New Implementation

Creating duplicate implementations is prohibited unless explicitly justified.

---

# Module Decision Matrix

Before creating a class ask

Platform Capability?

↓

Platform Service

Business Capability?

↓

Business Service

Industry Specific?

↓

Industry Plugin

Reusable Integration?

↓

Capability Plugin

Cross-Service Contract?

↓

SDK

Cross-Service Event?

↓

common-events

Infrastructure?

↓

Infrastructure Module

Never guess module ownership.

---

# Service Decomposition

Before introducing a new microservice ask

Can an existing bounded context own it?

Can an existing service evolve?

Will deployment independence improve?

Will team ownership improve?

Does it reduce coupling?

Does it improve scalability?

Create a new microservice only after answering YES where applicable.

---

# Architecture Review

Every feature requires an architecture review.

Questions

1.

Who owns this capability?

2.

Which bounded context owns it?

3.

Which aggregate owns it?

4.

Which service owns it?

5.

Which database owns it?

6.

Which event owns it?

7.

Which workflow owns it?

8.

Which plugin owns it?

9.

Which SDK exposes it?

10.

Who maintains it?

Architecture precedes implementation.

---

